<DOCNO> AP880701-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
international celebrities including 
music star paul simon have joined in a campaign to save the 
worlds largest example of portuguese colonial architecture in 
downtown salvador one of the western hemispheres oldest cities 
the 91acre district is now a slum 
it is called pelourinho the portuguese word for pillory 
stemming from salvadors former slave trade 
pelourinhos largely abandoned facades line the narrow streets 
of the city that also was brazils first capital and sometimes is 
known to outsiders as bahia the name of the coastal citys state 
in addition to paul simon other international celebrities 
involved in the campaign include the spanish crooner julio iglesias 
and akio morito president of the sony corp 
of the districts 978 buildings some dating as far back as the 
1500s 300 are close to collapse 48 are in ruins and about 10 
slide down hillsides every year in seasonal rainstorms according 
to maria del carmen coordinator of the savepelourinho campaign 
pelourinhos spacious mansions housed the elite when salvador 
was until 1763 the capital of portugals vast south american 
colony today it is a skid row home to prostitutes drug dealers 
and muggers 
pelourinho must be the worlds largest baroque slum said 
the bahia state secretary for culture gilberto gil who also is a 
popular singer and composer there are people in this city who 
havent dared venture into pelourinho for the past 20 years 
but for the first time authorities encouraged by private 
business have launched a massive campaign to clean up the winding 
streets and halfcollapsed mansions which in 1987 were designated 
by unesco as part of mankinds cultural heritage the buildings 
are protected from demolition by a local decree 
if we dont do something now the whole beautiful area will be 
completely irrecoverable in 10 years said ms del carmen an 
engineer 
but conversely it was after the unesco designation that the 
colonial buildings arcades courtyards and cobblestone streets 
began fell into greater disarray 
landlords refused to invest in their properties which were 
inhabited by tenants who could pay almost no rent gil said 
and they werent allowed to tear down their buildings so the 
strategy was to let the buildings literally fall down with 
tenants inside them 
so far the socalled historical park of pelourinho operating 
with 150 functionaries borrowed from various municipal government 
offices has raised the equivalent of about 7 million in 
government grants and loans ms del carmen said but organizers 
hope a media campaign that began in february directed at foreign 
and domestic business communities will bring in much more 
morita simon and iglesias are featured in 60second public 
service announcements asking for donations and encouraging 
businesses to invest in the area 
we need brazilians and others to feel responsible for the 
area to understand that brazil was born here and want to leave 
this for their children ms del carmen said most of the 
people who actually live here exist in subhuman conditions and 
could care less about pelourinho 
black groups have been some of the most active in rallying to 
save the decaying center as part of a slow but growing 
blackconsciousness movement in mixedrace brazil 
pelourinho was a major port of entry for slaves from africa from 
the 1500s through 1888 when slavery was abolished in brazil one 
of the areas most beautiful buildings the rosary of the blacks 
church was built over a period of 150 years by and for slaves 
every stone here was laid with the sweat of blacks said an 
area resident known only as zoinho we have to save this 
area its a monument to our suffering 
paulo de jesus 18 lives with his father and four brothers and 
sisters in two rooms of a massively subdivided old home he was 
born in pelourinho 
i wouldnt leave this place he said this is my home but 
if you knocked down our old home and built an apartment building in 
its place wed be much happier 
some residents are worried that increased property values will 
drive out longtime inhabitants 
we have to make sure we dont turn pelourinho into a picture 
postcard ms del carmen said the sense of community here is 
rich and very strong we need to bring in jobs schools health 
facilities and give people the chance to appreciate the fabulous 
historicl setting 
</TEXT>
