<TEXT>
president reagan sent a letter to president 
miguel de la madrid regarding mexicos refusal to extradite a 
puerto rican separatist accused of being a terrorist the us 
embassy said friday 
us ambassador charles pilliod delivered the letter to de la 
madrid friday afternoon us embassy spokesman arturo montano said 
he said he did not have any details of the message concerning 
37yearold william morales who was freed from a mexican prison 
june 24 and allowed to leave on a flight to cuba 
a spokesman at de la madrids office said the president would 
respond to reagans letter as soon as possible he did not 
comment on the contents of the reagan message but said de la madrid 
told pilliod he has instructed the foreign ministry to respond to a 
state department protest delivered earlier this week to the mexican 
ambassador in washington 
in washington state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said 
pilliod had personally carried the letter to de la madrid but she 
also would not discuss the contents 
mrs oakley said there had been no change in the us 
governments outrage at the release of morales 
the state deparment has called morales a convicted terrorist 
and murderer 
montano said pilliod returned to mexico thursday night from 
washington where he had been recalled for consultations tuesday 
mexico did not advise the united states that it had released 
morales until tuesday us officials have said 
mexican officials frequently characterized morales as a 
political fighter not a criminal and local news reports 
usually did not mention morales conviction in mexico for murder 
morales was released after serving five years of an eightyear 
sentence for the 1983 slaying of a mexican police officer and for 
entering the country illegally 
at the time of that killing morales was an escaped convict from 
the united states having fled in 1979 from a us prison after 
being convicted of weapons and explosives charges in new york 
after his capture in mexico the united states pressed without 
success for his extradition 
</TEXT>
