<TEXT>
officials could relax state restrictions 
on pesticide spraying in an effort to control the pear thrips an 
insect blamed for defoliating thousands of acres of maple trees in 
southern vermont 
officials of the state department of forests parks and 
recreation along with experts from the university of vermont and 
entomologists experienced with thrips from other northeastern 
states have come up with a research project designed to learn more 
about the insects habits life cycle and impact on maple crops and 
products 
pear thrips are insects whose feeding habits have damaged and 
weakened thousands of acres of vermont sugarbush particularly in 
bennington and windham counties 
the plans that experts have laid to improve the lot of maple 
trees may involve asking gov madeleine kunin to relax her 1986 
policy strictly limiting pesticide spraying by state agriculture 
and transportation officials 
william paine deputy commissioner of agriculture has done a 
control pesticide test spray on a sugarbush in londonderry with 
state permission to discover the most effective stage to spray in 
the thrips life cycle 
state forester bill guenther said recently the committee also 
wants to check for trends using an earthorbiting satellite that 
takes color coded infrared snapshots of vermont forest land 
the photos which would cost between 10000 and 12000 could 
give foresters a better idea of what next years maple crop will 
look like since the camera picks up signs of weakness and disease 
that human eyes can miss 
project members also plan to send out questionnaires to all 
known vermont sugarmakers asking them to comment on the extent of 
thrips damage 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

