<TEXT>
the constitutionality of the death penalty for 
juvenile killers again will be on the supreme courts agenda next 
term a welcome surprise for capital punishment foes 
leigh dingerson head of the national coalition to abolish the 
death penalty said its very encouraging i assumed it would be 
another couple of years before they took the issue up in another 
case 
henry schwarzschild of the american civil liberties union said 
the courts willingness to restudy the issue is very startling 
but he cautioned against reading too much into the courts 
announcement 
its foolish to try and predict what the court will do he 
said 
the justices on thursday provided a dramatic epilogue to their 
198788 term by agreeing to consider banning capital punishment for 
all juvenile murderers when the court returns for the next term on 
the first monday in october 
just 24 hours earlier the court had come close to banning the 
death penalty for those who commit murders before they are 16 
few expected it would move so quickly to reexamine capital 
punishment for juvenile killers 
but the justices said thursday they will use cases from georgia 
and missouri to reconsider the fate of young killers the court 
said it will decide sometime in 1989 whether use of the death 
penalty for anyone under 18 when the crime was committed violates 
the constitutions ban on cruel and unusual punishment 
the court will consider overturning the death sentences of 
georgia death row inmate jose martinez high who was 17 when he 
participated in a 1976 murder and missouri death row inmate heath 
wilkins who was 16 when he committed a 1985 murder 
high was just weeks shy of his 18th birthday when he took part 
in a gas station robbery in taliferro county ga in which an 
11yearold boy was shot to death 
wilkins helped rob an avondale mo liquor store nancy allen 
a store clerk was fatally stabbed 
the national coalition to abolish the death penalty said 30 
death row inmates nationwide out of a total of 2100 were under 
18 when they committed their crimes 
of the 100 men and women executed in the united states since the 
supreme court reinstated capital punishment in 1976 three 
committed their crimes when they were 17 since 1948 no one has 
been executed for a crime committed when he or she was younger than 
17 
if the supreme court bans the death penalty for those under 18 
it would affect most of the 37 states with death penalty laws 
including those that do not specify a minimum age for killers 
subject to capital punishment and states that specify age limits 
under 18 
on wednesday four justices said the death penalty is 
unconstitutional for those who were younger than 16 when they 
committed murder three justices said the constitution does not set 
such age limits for executions 
justice sandra day oconnor provided a fifth vote to throw out 
the death penalty for a convicted oklahoma killer who was 15 when 
he helped kill his former brotherinlaw but oconnor stopped just 
short of calling for abolition of capital punishment for killers 
under 16 
a key vote in next terms cases will be provided by justice 
anthony m kennedy who joined the court in february too late to 
participate in the oklahoma case 
in other action thursday the court 
agreed to study alleged race discrimination in alaskan salmon 
canneries setting the stage for an important sequel to the courts 
ruling on wednesday that makes it easier for workers to prove their 
bosses are guilty of illegal bias 
cleared away the last legal obstacle to a 180 million 
settlement with interest now worth some 240 million between 
vietnam veterans and manufacturers of the herbicide agent orange 
the court let stand rulings dismissing lawsuits by about 300 
veterans who challenged the settlement in which as many as 250000 
others could participate 
agreed to decide whether states may ban virtually all lawyer 
advertisements that feature testimonials or client endorsements 
the justices will review a california rule that presumes such ads 
are false or misleading 
</TEXT>
