<TEXT>
the first fiscal 1989 appropriations bill a 
barebones energy and water development package is a senate vote 
away from heading to president reagans desk 
the 1783 billion package worked out by house and senate 
negotiators cleared the house on a 38417 roll call thursday and is 
expected to win easy senate approval next week following the july 
fourth recess 
the spending bill the product of a tightmoney year is more 
noteworthy for what it lacks than what it contains 
there is no money to begin construction of the superconducting 
super collider and lawmakers say not a dime to start work on new 
army corps of engineers and bureau of reclamation water projects 
members of congress and staffers say they cant recall when even 
huge budget deficits prevented at least a few new dams or harbor 
projects from being tossed into the traditional pork barrel bill 
the administration is not happy about the lack of construction 
money for the ssc the multibillion dollar highenergy physics 
project that backers say is needed to keep the united states 
technologically competitive 
the white house however has not made any veto threats against 
the energy and water bill as it has against a number of the other 
12 spending bills under consideration in congress 
leaders on both sides the capitol agreed to give the energy 
department 100 million next year to continue preliminary work on 
the ssc but they said a decision to build it should be made by the 
next president 
the bill contains money to continue construction work on more 
than 200 corps and bureau water projects 
although the administration sought six new corps starts the 
house and senate appropriations committees approved none taking 
the position that just one new start would set off a clamor among 
lawmakers for more 
more than twothirds of the money in the bill 1316 billion 
is headed for the department of energy with that agencys nuclear 
activities for the defense department accounting for 81 billion 
the nondefense portion of the departments budget would finance 
a variety of activities including research into solar and other 
renewable forms of energy and environmental restoration and safety 
programs 
at the senates insistance the bill contains 3 million to 
study the greenhouse effect the global warming trend that 
scientists say threatens the earth with climate changes and rising 
ocean waters 
the corps would have 11 million less next year than in fiscal 
1988 to spend on dams harbors and other work including a growing 
number of shoreline erosion projects 
the bureau of reclamation which operates irrigation and power 
facilities in the west would get 40 million more in fiscal 1989 
with more than 40 percent of the money going to three large 
projects central arizona central utah and central valley in 
california 
</TEXT>
