<TEXT>
many nicaraguans are critical of their leftist 
government and dont believe it is democratic but they think 
soviet policies are better than those of the united states 
according to a private poll 
a survey presented thursday as the first independent poll of 
nicaraguan opinion under nine years of sandinista rule indicates 
strong support for president daniel ortega 85 percent opposition 
to us contra aid and 68 percent disapproval of us policies in 
central america 
asked what they most admire about the united states 42 percent 
of those polled said nothing which was the most prevalent 
answer 
the reagan administration for the past seven years has supported 
rebels attempting to overthrow the nicaraguan government 
the poll of 1129 adults in nicaragua was sponsored by the 
catholic university in managua and research groups in california 
and mexico 
william bollinger director of the cosponsoring interamerican 
research center of los angeles said the newly formed private 
nicaraguan institute of public opinion used accepted scientific 
polling methods employing students at catholic university which 
he described as the nations most politically neutral university 
the students interviewed 1129 adults selected at random in five 
types of managua neighborhoods on june 45 
bollinger did not offer a margin of error for the poll but he 
said at a news conference that several steps were taken to ensure 
its integrity and objectivity 
but he did note that many educated people who might have given 
antisandinista views have fled to the united states with their 
homes taken over by government officials and military officers he 
said about 27 percent of those polled worked for the government 
and they were the most supportive of the sandinistas 
thirtyeight percent of the respondents believed the ruling 
sandinistas management of the nicaraguan economy has been either 
bad or terrible while 36 percent described it as fair and only 22 
percent said it was good or excellent 
seventyfour percent of those interviewed said they rated their 
familys economic situation worse than a year ago while only 7 
percent said it was better 
fortyeight percent said they did not consider the sandinista 
government democratic while 40 percent said they did but there was 
general support for sandinista peace efforts and the governments 
foreign policies 
a majority supported incorporation of the contras into the 
countrys political life but most of those interviewed also said 
they doubted the fighting would end soon 
the overall results show the us economic blockade of 
nicaragua along with us support for the contra rebels has 
alienated even many antisandinista nicaraguans bollinger said 
the soviet union received higher positive responses than the 
united states among all income levels on several questions with 
higherincome groups being more prosoviet and prosandinista than 
poorer and lesseducated nicaraguans 
future polls the research group plans one of people in several 
latin american countries later this year will attempt to obtain 
more detail about reaction to soviet policies said bollinger 
only 1 percent of the respondents described us central 
american policy as excellent 7 percent called it good 17 percent 
said fair 40 percent said bad and 28 percent called it terrible 
asked the same question about soviet policy 14 percent said it 
was excellent 43 percent good 14 percent fair 9 percent bad and 
4 percent terrible 
in evaluating ortegas management of the government over the 
last four years 42 percent said it was good or excellent 29 
percent fair and 21 percent bad or terrible 
bollinger said this is a high rating in latin american terms he 
said in a similar poll conducted in el salvador only 13 percent of 
respondents gave president jose napoleon duarte a good or excellent 
rating 
the poll showed that 28 percent of those interviewed claimed 
affiliation with the ruling sandinista party 9 percent with 
liberal or conservative opposition parties and 59 percent said they 
belonged to no party 
bollinger said the nicaraguan government did not interfere with 
the survey even though laws apparently are still on the books 
prohibiting independent polling in the country 
