officials today denied western reports that 
police killed several peasants and brutally beat others who tried 
to stop the release of polluted water from a reservoir near beijing 
the official xinhua news agency late thursday issued the first 
official report of the june 21 protest during which peasants tried 
to stop a petrochemical company from releasing contaminated waste 
water from a reservoir into a local stream 
the peasants said the water would poison their wells and crops 
officials said the water level in the reservoir had risen too high 
and that there was danger of flooding 
wang zuoseng local communist party secretary criticized 
foreign reporting of the protest and accused western reporters of 
violating government regulations this week when they visited the 
reservoir in guce village 
authorities there turned away some western reporters this week 
and confiscated film and audio tapes 
guce which is under the beijing municipal administration is 37 
miles southwest of the city center 
wang cited the same regulation that was used last october to 
expel 14 western reporters from tibet following violent 
proindependence antichinese riots by tibetans in lhasa 
the regulation requires foreign reporters to apply for 
permission when traveling to report in areas open to foreigners 
reporters previously had interpreted it to apply to places outside 
beijing and officials have never before invoked it in greater 
beijing 
the new interpretation would significantly widen the scope of 
the regulation and severely limit foreign reporting in china 
at todays news conference wang said the july 21 protest was 
much smaller than peasant witnesses have said he denied witness 
accounts that thousands of armed police were brought in and scores 
of peasants were badly hurt 
