<TEXT>
aerospace experts developing star wars 
technology have successfully tested a tiny 2ounce rocket engine 
designed to power satellitebased missile killers 
the engine tested at rocketdynes santa susana field laboratory 
on thursday is slated for use as a directional thruster for a 
spacebased interceptor in the strategic defense initiative program 
the goal is to neutralize incoming enemy nuclear missiles before 
they reenter the atmosphere by using lasers and interceptor 
rockets 
the new engine dubbed by designers as the most efficient in the 
free world would guide the interceptor from its base on a 
satellite toward an approaching nuclear missile the missile would 
be destroyed on impact 
officials from the air force space division rockwell 
international and rocketdyne called the test successful praising 
the engines weighttothrust ratio a measure of its power and 
efficiency thrust is the forward force produced in reaction to 
gases escaping rearward from the engine 
the engines we were running with around five years ago were 
1to20 said ernie bunch a rocketdyne engineer in the 
spacebased interceptor or sabir program 
the tiny engine tested has a weighttothrust ratio of 
1to1200 said frank patota engineer in charge of the test area 
the engine was fired or pulsed for five milliseconds and then 
was shut off for 110 of a second this cycle was repeated dozens 
of times during each of the three testings the result sounded like 
machine gun fire 
the interceptor rockets would be equipped with four of the 
tested engines and four smaller thrusters 
