<TEXT>
romanias move to shut down a hungarian 
consulate was unprecedented in the warsaw pact alliance and shows 
how historically rooted ethnic strife can foul up sovietled 
attempts to forge unity in east europe 
seventy years after romania gained the region of transylvania 
from hungary the two neighbors are still bickering over treatment 
of the 17 million ethnic hungarians who live in the fictional 
homeland of count dracula 
in the past two years the dispute has escalated sharply 
pointing up the difference between hungarys reformminded 
communism and the inflexible regime of nicolae ceausescu which is 
increasingly isolated even among its east bloc allies 
romanias decision tuesday to close the general consulate in 
clujnapoca in transylvania came in retaliation for an 
antiromanian rally in budapest the hungarian capital on monday 
night about 50000 hungarians protested romanias plans to destroy 
7000 romanian villages including hundreds of hungarian 
communities 
today the hungarian parliament condemned the resettlement plan 
and urged bucharest to reconsider the move 
hungary maintains the plan would destroy the hungarians 
cultural heritage and ultimately wipe out hungarian and other 
minorities in romania 
romanian officials said the villages to be razed by the year 
2000 would be replaced by agriculturalindustrial centers designed 
to remove differences between country and city dwellers 
hungarian officials at a mass meeting on budapests heroes 
square monday evening said hungary probably will seek international 
support to pressure romania to cancel the project 
but ceausescu on tuesday rejected hungarian protests as 
nationalistic chauvinistic antiromanian and antisocialist 
ceausescus address indicated that relations have reached their 
lowest ebb in postwar communist history 
hungary long has complained about acts of official 
discrimination against its hungarian minority across the border and 
asserted that its people are denied important cultural and ethnic 
rights 
the ethnic hungarians known in romania as magyars live in a 
21000squaremile area of some of the most picturesque mountain 
and farm land in the balkans 
the land was under hungarian control for nine centuries but was 
given to romania on dec 1 1919 as part of the dismemberment of 
the austrohungarian empire after world war i 
nazi dictator adolf hitler returned much of the land to hungary 
during world war ii in appreciation of the loyalty of the countrys 
ruler adm nicholas horthy after the war the allies gave 
transylvania back to romania 
the romanians support their claim to the land by arguing that 
romanized dacians their apparent ancestors stayed in the area 
after the romans withdrew from what is now romania in the 3rd 
century ad 
but hungarian scholars maintain the dacians withdrew along with 
their roman protectors south of the danube river and that the 
magyars found a largely empty country when they drifted in from 
asia in the 9th century 
budapest relinquished its claim to transylvania by signing the 
1975 helsinki agreements recognizing postwar borders but the 
hungarian government and people remain deeply interested in the 
areas hungarian minority 
treatment of national minorities in romania is synonymous with 
south african apartheid hungarian poet gyula illyes said 10 
years ago 
the romanian government says its treatment of the hungarian and 
german minorities is fair it accuses budapest of chauvinism and 
interfererence in its internal affairs and says hungary is trying 
to regain transylvania 
last april hungary strongly criticized romania for decreeing 
that romanianlanguage place names must be used for cities and 
villages traditionally known to the countrys ethnic minorities in 
their own language 
in march hungary took the unprecedented action of approving 
about 6 million to help thousands of ethnic hungarian refugees who 
have fled the shortages and harsh living conditions in romania 
the refugees believed to number up to 20000 now also include 
several hundred romanian speakers who are seeking to settle in the 
west 
