<TEXT>
grasshoppers and other insects left hungry by 
the drought are wreaking havoc on what remains in farm fields 
while young trees are depending on young people scooping buckets of 
water from city lakes to sustain them 
the good news is a low mosquito population this summer but 
id rather have the moisture on my grass says ross green of 
the metropolitan mosquito control district in st paul 
yellowjackets and wasps may take the place of mosquitoes and be 
more aggressive at picnics and near garbage cans as they search for 
food said university of minnesota entomologist jeffrey hahn 
it could be that they just die from a lack of food but it 
also could be that they will be driven to interact with people when 
