<TEXT>
lowerranking government officials and 
intellectuals linked to the banned trade union solidarity met 
secretly this week to try to reopen dialogue stymied since the 
imposition of martial law in 1981 
the discussions which one participant described as in the 
nature of a first meeting focused on the possibility of an 
anticrisis pact in which the two sides would unite behind a 
program to end the countrys economic crisis 
it was certainly a success that this meeting took place 
according to the participant referring to the virtual absence of 
direct talks between the government and opposition in poland since 
the imposition of martial law in 1981 
martial law was lifted in 1983 but opposition groups including 
the solidarity trade union remain officially banned 
the fourhour meeting tuesday took place with the knowledge of 
polish leader gen wojciech jaruzelski and politiburo member jozef 
czyrek said a source familiar with the event he said it might 
lead to meetings with participation of higherranking officials 
the participant speaking on condition of anonymity said the 
meeting ended with a decision for a later meeting that would be 
more concrete devoted to selected problems no date was set 
about 25 people were invited by marek goliszewski editor of the 
monthly newspaper konfrontacja confrontation and its editorial 
board the publication linked with the official national unity 
organization pron began publishing in january and has been 
promoting the anticrisis pact idea 
goliszewski confirmed he called the meeting other sources from 
the opposition and the official side demanding anonymity provided 
details to the associated press 
among those reported attending from the opposition were 
solidarity advisers bronislaw geremek and ryszard bugaj andrzej 
stelmachowski president of the catholic intellectuals club of 
warsaw and aleksander paszynski head of a nationwide association 
of private entrepreneurs which has applied for official recognition 
from the authorities were col stanislaw kwiatkowski head of 
the government public opinion polling center mariusz gulczynski 
deputy director of the institute of state and law of the polish 
academy of sciences and a parliamentary communist party leader 
ryszard wojna the sources said 
the meeting was known to be controversial within the opposition 
which is wary of being used one roman catholic intellectual 
lawyer tadeusz mazowiecki said he stayed away because i thought 
it wasnt wise to hold such a meeting at this time 
there were no politicians there was no walesa said the 
participant referring to solidarity chief lech walesa 
of the representatives from the official side he said they 
are important advisers but of lower rank 
the discussion was definitely a political one an outlining 
of positions or stands he said and i think that the next 
meeting will be more pragmatic or technical 
the sources said some of the participants insisted it not be 
publicized it took place on neutral grounds a hall at warsaw 
university he said 
the source familiar with the meeting said it was an opportunity 
for the government to poll a broad spectrum of the opposition on 
what solutions it might accept to solve polands problems 
the nation was hit by a wave of strikes last month and there has 
been little public enthusiasm for government economic reform steps 
including steep price increases to save polands debtburdened and 
inefficient economy 
both sides expressed approval of the need for rapid changes in 
the economy the source said but the opposition stressed the 
opinion that the changes have to be very radical 
the most emotional discussion was reported to focus on trade 
unions with the opposition demanding legalization of solidarity a 
suggestion rejected by the officials the opposition side said it 
was willing to hear other government proposals that would create 
trade union pluralism the source said 
the sides agreed on the desirability of independent 
associations political discussion clubs and a coalition form 
of governing in which representatives of independent circles 
would enter the government and the parliament the source said 
but the officials taking part in the discussion said they had no 
authority to make firm offers and would have to consult with their 
superiors while the opposition stressed that it was not interested 
in artificial actions from the government or attempts to split 
its ranks said the source 
geremek proposed talks on an anticrisis pact in an 
interview published by konfrontacja earlier this year czyrek the 
politburo member repeated the formulation in an interview 
published in may 
however the two sides have been at odds publically over what the 
pact would cover and who would be the governments negotiating 
partner 
officials have said the government could not talk to groups paid 
by a foreign power or people who want the situation in poland to 
worsen descriptions normally applied by the official media to 
solidarity 
the source said such language was absent from tuesdays meeting 
