china on friday urged all cambodian factions to 
form a coalition government as vietnam withdraws its forces 
shifting policy in an apparent effort to keep the cambodian khmer 
rouge from becoming dominant 
china said that once an interim government is established a 
freeze should be imposed on kampuchean cambodian forces of all 
factions and these factions should refrain from interfering in 
free general elections 
the chinese government the main ally of the communist khmer 
rouge and other factions in cambodias antivietnamese resistance 
previously insisted no national reconciliation could take place in 
cambodia until vietnam withdrew all its troops vietnam invaded 
cambodia in late 1978 ousted the khmer rouge government and 
installed another communist regime 
cambodian prime minister hun sen and some countries including 
the united states have expressed concern that vietnams withdrawal 
will create an opening for the khmer rouge to again seize power 
the khmer rouge came to power after defeating the usbacked 
government in the spring of 1975 according to some estimates up 
to 3 million cambodians were killed under the khmer rouge regime 
china has backed a threeparty antivietnamese coalition headed 
by former cambodian prince norodom sihanouk the coalition includes 
sihanouks followers the khmer rouge and a noncommunist group 
under son sann 
the khmer rouge is believed to have a stronger fighting force 
than its coalition partners 
in a proposal issued by the foreign ministry china said vietnam 
should withdraw all of its estimated 140000 troops at the 
earliest possible date and the three resistance groups and hun 
sen should form a provisional government headed by sihanouk while 
vietnam pulls out 
vietnam said this week it had begun withdrawing 50000 troops 
and its military command from cambodia in an operation to be 
completed in december it said it will have removed all of its 
forces by 1990 
the foreign ministry proposal called for practical and 
effective international supervision of vietnams troop 
withdrawal the maintenance of peace in cambodia and free elections 
it did not elaborate on which countries it envisioned joining in 
the supervision or if they should send troops to form a 
peacekeeping force 
chinas proposal appeared timed for consideration by the four 
cambodian parties at informal talks to be held in indonesia later 
this month 
its conciliatory tone was in sharp contrast to other recent 
chinese statements that have called vietnams troop withdrawal plan 
inadequate and a possible hoax 
