<TEXT>
conservation groups applauded a 
decision friday by the international timber industry to promote 
environmentconscious logging in the amazon jungle the worlds 
largest tropical rainforest 
the usbased world wildlife fund said the decision the first 
of its kind by the timber industry could slow destruction of the 
amazon rainforest a key regulator of the worlds weather 
the international tropical timber organization an association 
of 42 producing and consuming countries approved a 4 million 
logging and conservation project in the remote jungle state of 
acre on brazils border with bolivia 2800 miles northwest of rio 
de janeiro 
the project calls for integrated development of jungle 
products such as brazil nuts and rubber as well as timber it 
also calls for loggers to consult with environmental groups 
government agencies native indians and local workers to plan 
longterm development to preserve the rainforest 
this was the big one we hope the acre project can serve as a 
model not just for the rest of the amazon but for all tropical 
forests adam markham press spokesman for the world wildlife 
fund told the ap at the end of a 10day meeting of the timber 
organization 
the organizations members control 95 percent of the worlds 
56 billion tropical timber trade 
as timber trade shifts away from the shrinking forests of africa 
and southeast asia the mahoganyrich amazon is seen as the next 
great source of hardwood 
but conservationists are worried about the effect on the climate 
of uncontrolled logging in the amazon basin a 2 million 
squaremile region as large as europe that covers parts of seven 
south american countries and contains a third of the worlds 
rainforest 
already the amazon forest is disappearing at the rate of some 27 
million acres a year mostly at the hands of small farmers and 
ranchers who cut and burn the trees markham said 
the rainforest is a gaseous sink for carbon dioxide the trees 
soak it up if we cut them down theres no way to get rid of the 
gas and that contributes to the greenhouse effect he said 
the greenhouse effect is a gradual warming of the earths 
surface because of excessive carbon dioxide and pollutants in the 
atmosphere that trap the suns heat like a greenhouse it is 
thought to be a possible cause of the current drought in the us 
midwest 
the acre project which will get about 3 million from the 
brazilan government and the rest from the timber organization is 
the largest approved since the organization was founded in 1986 
smaller conservation programs similar to the acre project were 
approved for bolivia and ecuador 
other proposals approved at the rio meeting were 
development of a news market service to help producing 
countries market better 
standardization of timber specifications among member 
countries to cut waste caused by conflicting measurements 
improvement of harvesting and processing equipment 
the next meeting of the organization is scheduled for november 
in yokohama japan 
