<TEXT>
environmentalists are mobilizing 
to save whats left of brazils oncevast atlantic forest the 
nations picturepostcard front door 
one of the species of trees near extinction is the brazilwood 
or paubrazil which gave the country its name 
when portuguese explorers discovered brazil in 1500 the 
atlantic forest covered some 170000 square miles along a 
3000mile coastal strip 
today with 80 million of the countrys 143 million people and 
most of its heavy industry crowded into the coastal zone only 
about 3 percent of the original primary forest remains in 
scattered patches 
some of the forests rare monkeys birds and trees many found 
nowhere else in the world face extinction 
we are in the process of destroying an entire ecosystem but 
theres still time to save whats left and prevent total tragedy 
said rodrigo lara mesquita the chairman of a group called the 
sos atlantic forest foundation 
the foundation has strong economic and political influence 
mesquita is an heir of the family that for a century has 
controlled the influential o estado de s paulo newspaper and media 
group others running sos include two multimillionaire 
industrialists the president of the countrys largest university 
and a retired admiral 
since 1986 the foundation has raised the equivalent of more 
than 4 million for nationwide newspaper and television publicity 
it intends to collect more for the satellite mapping of the forest 
zone and for actual conservation programs where the remaining 
forest is thickest 
this group is powerful and well organized said russell a 
mittermeier international vice chairman of the washingtonbased 
world wildlife fund and a consultant to the atlantic forest 
organization its not radical as unfortunately was the case 
with many well meaning but ineffective environmental groups that 
sprang up in the united states in the 1960s im very optimistic 
mittermeier has been coming to brazil since 1971 principally to 
work with atlantic forests endangered monkey species 
he said in an interview in rio de janeiro that brazil probably 
has the best chance for success of the three highestpriority 
ecological problems in the world the tropical south american 
andes in colombia ecuador and peru the african island of 
madagascar and the atlantic forest 
here in the atlantic forest it really is possible to save the 
remnants mittermeier said he mentioned specifically the 
muriqui south americas largest primate of which fewer than 100 
remain the golden lion tamarin another endangered monkey with 
about 400 left the increasingly scarce redtailed parrot the rare 
and valuable jacaranda tree and the almost extinct paubrazil 
today with few exceptions the only place you can still see 
paubrasil is in a botanical garden lamented mesquita 
early portuguese pioneers chopped down all the brazilwood they 
could find to extract dye later settlers hacked away the coastal 
forest to make way for sugarcane and coffee plantations and for 
settlements 
the sos atlantic forest foundations logotype is a stylized 
greenyellowandblue brazilian flag but with part of the green 
ripped away 
a foundation poster shows a map of brazil with an outline of the 
atlantic forest as it existed in 1500 with the words in 
portuguese i used to be like this then there is a map showing 
the scattered forest pockets left today and the words i wound up 
like this 
the foundations first specific project is to be in a 
stillrelatively untouched forest zone covering 3500 square miles 
along the coasts of the southeastern states of sao paulo and 
parana it intends to set up two ecological bases and buy a 
patroltype boat to sound the alarm against illegal tree cutting 
and the banned netting of coastal fish shrimp and oysters 
invasion of that region has long gone unpunished sos 
chairman mesquita said but we think we can stop it were 
organized weve got money and we have access to the authorities 
and the media 
the foundation also supported lobby efforts in brazils congress 
to place in the draft of a new constitution the legal concept of 
ecological crime 
were also attempting a process of environmental education 
said ibsen de gusmao camara the former admiral who now is a member 
of the sos board a lot of brazilians think development 
automatically means physical occupation its not that they 
purposely want to destroy the environment they just dont know any 
better 
well never see the atlantic forest again as it once was he 
added thats impossible but we will put a stop to the 
destruction and preserve and build up the forests genetic 
library 
