<TEXT>
newsletter editor michael b woods remembers 
better times for analyzing overthecounter stocks 
last year this time you could see it when we picked a 
stock he said it moved right away now we pick a stock it 
may not budge 
meet another group of the walking wounded from last octobers 
stock market crash entrepreneurs who produce the nations 
investment newsletters 
woods and other small purveyors of stockmarket advice are 
finding their readership has slipped almost as badly as the dow 
jones average over the past year 
this will be the first year my business will not have grown 
said robert j nurock publisher of the astute investor based in 
nearby paoli even given the fact that i missed calling the 
crash the response to my advertising has been especially poor 
nurock said subscriptions to his astute investor have dropped by 
28 percent since peaking in january 1987 
since the crash individual investors wary of the impact of 
program trading on the market and the prospect of another collapse 
largely have abandoned stocks the market for advice good or 
otherwise is off sharply 
even before october dark clouds were gathering for the 
newsletters the emergence of mutual funds as major investment 
vehicles reduced the need to choose individual stocks at the same 
time the fiveyear bull market created a proliferation of 
investment advice in newspapers and magazines and on television 
suddenly we had all this competition said woods 36 a 
former newspaper reporter we were like the race tracks when 
casino gambling came along 
martin zweig a widely known market pundit and editor of two new 
york newsletters agreed 
it used to be when you were right business was good he 
told the philadelphia inquirer now you never know basically 
the business hasnt been healthy for a couple of years now 
newsletter issuers range from standard amp poors corp of new 
york to individuals armed with little more than a home computer and 
their hunches 
some publications have thrived in the postcrash environment 
zweig said the subscription base of his zweig forecast has 
increased by 4000 to 14000 since late november overall revenue 
is running 80 percent ahead of last year he said 
a oneyear subscription to zweigs newsletter published every 
three weeks costs 245 
zweig a former finance professor and a graduate of the 
university of pennsylvanias wharton school attributes his 
circulation surge to performance according to a rating of 
investment newsletters by hulbert financial digest zweig forecast 
was the secondbest performer in the fiveyear period that ended 
march 31 posting an 189 percent annual return on a portfolio of 
selected stocks 
we basically called the crash zweig said on oct 19 we 
were only 8 percent invested in stocks 
similarly james stack publisher of investech market analyst a 
newsletter published out of whitefish mont said he began 
recommending that his clients get out of the market in april 1987 
by early october he was out of the market 
our subscription rate is up 28 percent over the past eight 
months said stack a former ibm engineer who began his 
newsletter six years ago 
stack noted he did not escape the year unscathed clients who 
heeded his advice to abandon the market in april found themselves 
sitting on the sidelines during last summers runup 
we were getting out while the bull market was still going 
strong he said we had a 25 percent cancellation rate in 
august which is phenomenally high for us it was very depressing 
woods a philadelphian who edits the new yorkbased publication 
otc review special situations said circulation peaked at 5000 
subscriptions in the spring of 1987 since then subscriptions to 
the monthly newsletter priced at 150 annually have dropped by 
half despite a relatively robust recovery by overthecounter 
stocks 
the owner of the newsletter robert j flaherty asked woods to 
edit it at home and contracted circulation services to an outside 
firm woods said his april 1 move into a secondfloor bedroom was 
not a response to the crash but he acknowledged that industry 
costcutting is in vogue 
a lot of newsletters are running close to the bone now he 
said so far i havent suffered any real personal damage but 
theres no doubt we are in for some lean times 
