<TEXT>
us supercomputer manufacturers said friday they 
were disappointed with the japanese governments failure to 
purchase usmade supercomputers despite japans commitment last 
year to encourage such procurements 
a bilateral agreement to promote though not guarantee japanese 
publicsector purchases of us supercomputers went into effect 
last august after the united states complained that the japanese 
government was favoring japanese supercomputers over their american 
counterparts 
i think disappointed is the word to describe us computer 
makers feeling toward japanese government procurement of american 
supercomputers john mcphee director of the us commerce 
departments office of computers and business equipment told 
reporters at the foreign correspondents club of japan 
supercomputers are advancedtechnology computers that perform 
complex calculations at rapid speed and are used in such fields as 
science engineering and the military 
mcphee said the first three government procurements in japan 
since the agreement went into effect by the staterun tohoku and 
hokkaido universities and the high energy physics laboratory went 
to nec and hitachi which along with fujitsu are japans leading 
computer makers 
its curious to us as we look at the data to see that us 
firms have 8085 percent of the supercomputer market in the rest 
of the world but a relatively small share of the private sector in 
japan and until recently had no installations in the japanese 
government mcphee said 
mcphee headed a delegation of six us supercomputer 
manufacturers which conducted a trade seminar and exhibition in 
tokyo this week the delegation consisted of cray research inc 
eta systems inc evans amp sutherland computer corp myrias 
computer corp prime computer inc and scientific computer 
systems corp 
the solutions to performance problems that these firms bring 
to the market are an attractive package for japanese users 
mcphee said 
the delegation came to japan to familiarize potential japanese 
clients with their technology and to study possible joint marketing 
of their products with japanese partners said lee adamson prime 
