<TEXT>
thousands of companies may still be unaware of 
the need to meet todays deadline for reporting release of any one 
of 328 different toxic chemicals into the environment last year 
says an industry representative 
theres a tremendous amount of misunderstanding out there 
said theresa pugh dealing with the issue for the national 
association of manufacturers 
the confusion arises because many businesses have assumed the 
law applies only to chemical companies and no one has been able to 
mount a loud enough publicity campaign she said 
throughout nam in the past month weve had about 1000 calls 
inquiring whether a business is covered by the law and i can count 
on the fingers of one hand those that werent she said thursday 
a new york public relations firm chimed in today with evidence 
backing up her point interviews with representatives of 81 
companies covered by the new law found only 24 had a program to 
answer questions at installations using the chemicals 
many companies in the food transportation and instruments 
industries appear to be largely unprepared said a statement from 
ketchum public affairs part of ketchum communications inc 
the 1986 law requiring the reports was one response of congress 
to the disastrous leak in bhopal india of methyl isocyanate in 
1984 that killed almost 3000 people 
the law potentially applies to almost all manufacturers the 
standard industrial classification codes 20 through 39 of the 
commerce department the environmental protection agency has 
certain discretion to expand it 
the agency estimates that 30000 installations probably should 
file fivepage forms on an average of 10 different chemicals a 
total of 15 million pages 
not every company must report only those with 10 or more 
employees that manufacture import or process 75000 pounds per 
year of any of the chemicals or use 10000 pounds per year these 
threshold quantities decline in future years 
companies that process a chemical make it an ingredient of a 
product for an example an example of use on the other hand is 
cleaning with a chemical 
affected companies must report all deliberate and accidental 
releases as well as leaks if measurements or calculations are 
unavailable engineering judgment may be used 
reports must be made to epa and to state authorities 
environmentalists are counting on the accessibility of the data 
in computer form to generate political support for a broader and 
tighter program of regulation 
ill tell you what the public reaction is going to be its 
not going to like the fact that the environment is used as a 
dumping ground for all these chemicals said debbie sheiman of 
the natural resources defense council 
chris cathcart of the chemical manufacturers association whose 
trade group has sent emissaries from its own ranks and from members 
into hundreds of newspaper offices to explain whats coming said 
it would not be a good thing if people just drew conclusions 
from the numbers 
the association has encouraged member companies to release forms 
publicly as they file them and cathcart said the group is telling 
people you should talk to people you have confidence in if 
anything about the reports arouses concern 
some of the numbers are going to be huge about 22 billion 
pounds of toluene a common petrochemical are released to the air 
nationwide each year 
no one has a good idea of the total for all the covered 
chemicals or the damage being done 
the 328 chemicals were specified by congress from lists used by 
new jersey and maryland programs epa says slightly more than half 
can cause cancer at least in animals and 44 percent are acutely 
toxic 
several years ago epa estimated that airborne chemicals were 
causing 2000 annual deaths from cancer 
</TEXT>
