<TEXT>
csx corp on friday reported a 
secondquarter loss of 160 million mainly because of a 778 
million special charge that will in part cover severance payments 
to laidoff employees 
excluding the charge second quarter earnings would have been 
332 million or 212 per share in the yearago quarter the 
transportation energy and technology conglomerate earned 114 
million or 74 cents a share 
of the special charge 592 million will be used for costs 
related to reducing the rail labor force to about 30000 employees 
about 8200 employees will receive payments ranging from 30000 
to 50000 except for locomotive enginemen who are covered under 
an existing program that calls for payments of 75000 
the remaining 186 million of the special charge covers various 
costs and claims pending against csx and certain subsidiaries 
those costs are expected to result from litigation and negotiated 
settlements 
csx president and chief operating officer john w snow said the 
employee reduction program is part of csx transportations effort 
to match the number of rail employees with the operating 
requirements of the rail system csx transportation is a subsidiary 
of csx corp 
snow said csx corp since its formation in 1980 has reduced 
the physical base of csx transportation from 26748 route miles 
3343 locomotives and 175281 freight cars at yearend 1981 to 
21494 route miles 2633 locomotives and 116063 freight cars at 
yearend 1987 
for the first six months of 1988 csx lost 95 million compared 
with earnings of 199 million or 129 per share for the first 
half of 1987 
without the special charge first half earnings would have been 
397 million or 252 per share 
